T1  - A woman's place is in the… startup! Crowdfunder judgments, implicit bias, and the stereotype content model
AU  - Johnson, Michael A.
AU  - Stevenson, Regan M.
AU  - Letwin, Chaim R.
JO  - Journal of Business Venturing
VL  - 33
IS  - 6
SP  - 813
EP  - 831
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2018/11/01/
SN  - 0883-9026
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jbusvent.2018.04.003
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0883902616302798
AB  - We examine investor stereotypes and implicit bias in crowdfunding decisions. Prior research in formal venture capital settings demonstrates that investors tend to have a funding bias against women. However, in crowdfunding – wherein a ‘crowd’ of amateur investors make relatively small investments in new companies – our empirical observations reveal a funding advantage for women. We explain the causal mechanism underlying this counterintuitive finding by drawing upon stereotype content theory and testing a dual path moderated-mediation model. Based on archival data and a follow-up experiment, our findings suggest common gender biases held by amateur investors function to increase female stereotype perceptions in the form of trustworthiness judgments, which subsequently increases investors' willingness to invest in early-stage women-led ventures. We discuss our results with specific attention to how our findings extend the entrepreneurship funding literature as well as the gender dynamics literature in entrepreneurship and organization research more broadly.
